<section id="fs-idm400081744">
<title>Comprehension Questions</title>
<exercise id="fs-idm394420016">
<problem id="fs-idm381017264">
<para id="fs-idm388701664">What are Walker’s expectations of his audience?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm413203392">
<problem id="fs-idm411325104">
<para id="fs-idm403962928">Why would Walker suggest that some of the members of his audience would need to have others read the pamphlet to them? Why would the pamphlet be “designed more particularly for them”?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm683329776">
<problem id="fs-idm683519088">
<para id="fs-idm375854176">What does Walker say will be the ultimate solution to the problem of slavery? What must enslaved people do in preparation for that solution?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm399260640">
<problem id="fs-idm397447744">
<para id="fs-idm379201936">What does Walker mean when he writes, “. . . the day they do it they are gone”?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm395822368">
<problem id="fs-idm408139360">
<para id="fs-idm397286000">According to Walker, how do African American slaves differ from other groups? How might this difference have instilled a sense of identity in the minds of Walker’s readers?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm359000848">
<problem id="fs-idm379181040">
<para id="fs-idm416223088">Why does Walker describe the odd juxtaposition of two articles in a newspaper? What does he see as ironic about this juxtaposition?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm400235280">
<problem id="fs-idm394977504">
<para id="fs-idm414908528">To whom is Walker referring to as “they”?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm404385072">
<problem id="fs-idm410064016">
<para id="fs-idm395529360">How does Walker use religious principles to make his audience aware of their unjust treatment?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm399788928">
<problem id="fs-idm394823648">
<para id="fs-idm394156608">Why might Walker have decided to include a quote from former President Jefferson in his pamphlet?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm358309648">
<problem id="fs-idm380264912">
<para id="fs-idm405163968">What is the “great work” that Walker expected his readers to accomplish?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm403982752">
<problem id="fs-idm393046832">
<para id="fs-idm395511200">Why does Walker believe in the importance of education and religion? Which group does he believe may have been particularly reluctant to embrace education and religion?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm415454880">
<problem id="fs-idm675892960">
<para id="fs-idm684017216">How does Walker use his anecdote about the “pretended preacher” to point out the hypocrisy of religious officials and slaveholders?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
<exercise id="fs-idm380312512">
<problem id="fs-idm683377408">
<para id="fs-idm415797616">What does Walker suggest might happen if white Americans do not repent for the sin of slavery?</para>
</problem>
</exercise>
